# Service/Repository Safe Update Pattern Rule

When creating or modifying Service or Repository layers that access the database, always use the Safe Update pattern to ensure Entity Framework Foreign Keys are updated properly and tracked correctly.

## Core Requirements

### 1. Use Safe Update Pattern
- Always use `SafeUpdateAsync<T>()` method from `BaseService` for entity updates
- Never directly modify entities without fetching them from the database first
- This prevents EF change tracking issues with navigation properties

### 2. Database Access Patterns
- Services/Repositories should inherit from `BaseService` when possible
- Use the `_dbContextFactory` pattern for database access
- Implement proper entity ID retrieval in derived classes

### 3. Entity Update Guidelines
- Fetch existing entity from database before updates
- Apply changes through the update action parameter
- Let Entity Framework handle change tracking properly

## Implementation Examples

### ✅ Good - Using Safe Update Pattern
```csharp
public class ViolationService : BaseService
{
    public ViolationService(IDbContextFactory<ApplicationDbContext> dbContextFactory) 
        : base(dbContextFactory) { }

    public async Task UpdateViolationAsync(Violation violation)
    {
        await SafeUpdateAsync(violation, existingViolation =>
        {
            existingViolation.Description = violation.Description;
            existingViolation.Status = violation.Status;
            existingViolation.ViolationTypeId = violation.ViolationTypeId;
            // Navigation properties will be properly tracked
        });
    }

    protected override object GetEntityId<T>(T entity)
    {
        return entity switch
        {
            Violation violation => violation.Id,
            ViolationType violationType => violationType.Id,
            _ => throw new NotSupportedException($"Entity type {typeof(T).Name} not supported")
        };
    }
}
```

### ❌ Bad - Direct Entity Modification
```csharp
public class ViolationService
{
    private readonly ApplicationDbContext _context;

    public async Task UpdateViolationAsync(Violation violation)
    {
        // ❌ Bad - Directly updating without fetching from database
        _context.Violations.Update(violation);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
        // This can cause navigation property tracking issues
    }
}
```

### ❌ Bad - Manual Entity Fetching
```csharp
public async Task UpdateViolationAsync(Violation violation)
{
    using var context = _dbContextFactory.CreateDbContext();
    
    // ❌ Bad - Manual fetching without using SafeUpdate pattern
    var existing = await context.Violations.FindAsync(violation.Id);
    if (existing != null)
    {
        existing.Description = violation.Description;
        existing.Status = violation.Status;
        await context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

## Service/Repository Structure Pattern
```csharp
public class ExampleService : BaseService
{
    public ExampleService(IDbContextFactory<ApplicationDbContext> dbContextFactory) 
        : base(dbContextFactory) { }

    // ✅ Good - Use SafeUpdateAsync for all entity updates
    public async Task UpdateEntityAsync(Entity entity)
    {
        await SafeUpdateAsync(entity, existingEntity =>
        {
            // Apply all updates here
            existingEntity.Property1 = entity.Property1;
            existingEntity.Property2 = entity.Property2;
            existingEntity.NavigationPropertyId = entity.NavigationPropertyId;
        });
    }

    // ✅ Good - Implement GetEntityId for all entity types
    protected override object GetEntityId<T>(T entity)
    {
        return entity switch
        {
            Entity e => e.Id,
            AnotherEntity ae => ae.Id,
            _ => throw new NotSupportedException($"Entity type {typeof(T).Name} not supported")
        };
    }
}
```

## Validation Checklist
- [ ] Service/Repository inherits from `BaseService`
- [ ] All entity updates use `SafeUpdateAsync<T>()`
- [ ] `GetEntityId<T>()` is properly implemented for all entity types
- [ ] No direct `context.Set<T>().Update()` calls
- [ ] No manual entity fetching and updating
- [ ] Navigation properties are properly handled

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid
1. Direct entity updates without fetching from database
2. Manual context management without SafeUpdate pattern
3. Direct `Update()` calls on DbSet
4. Modifying entities without proper change tracking
5. Not implementing `GetEntityId<T>()` method

## Benefits of Safe Update Pattern
- Prevents EF change tracking issues
- Ensures navigation properties are properly updated
- Maintains data consistency
- Reduces bugs related to entity state management
- Provides consistent update behavior across all services

This rule ensures that all database operations in Service/Repository layers follow the Safe Update pattern for proper Entity Framework behavior.
